# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Speed Insights for the motor control board frontend application.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- **Modified**: `package.json`
  - Added `@vercel/speed-insights` (v1.3.1) as a dependency
- **Modified**: `package-lock.json`
  - Updated lock file with the new dependency and its transitive dependencies (180 packages)

### 2. Speed Insights Integration
- **Modified**: `src/main.jsx`
  - Imported `SpeedInsights` component from `@vercel/speed-insights/react`
  - Added `<SpeedInsights />` component within the React.StrictMode wrapper, after the Toaster component
  - This ensures Speed Insights tracks performance metrics across all pages of the application

## Implementation Details

This is a React application built with Vite, so I followed the Vercel Speed Insights documentation for React/Create React App integration:

1. Installed the `@vercel/speed-insights` package via npm
2. Imported the `SpeedInsights` component from `@vercel/speed-insights/react` 
3. Added the component to the root render in `main.jsx`

The `<SpeedInsights />` component is a wrapper around the tracking script that provides seamless integration with React. It will automatically:
- Load the Speed Insights tracking script from `/_vercel/speed-insights/script.js`
- Track Core Web Vitals and other performance metrics
- Send data to the Vercel dashboard when the app is deployed

## Verification

- ✅ Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
- ✅ No linting errors introduced
- ✅ All dependencies properly installed and lock file updated
- ✅ Build artifacts (dist/) correctly excluded from git tracking

## Next Steps

After deployment to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard (Project → Speed Insights tab)
2. Deploy the application 
3. Verify that `/_vercel/speed-insights/script.js` is accessible
4. Wait for user traffic to start seeing performance data in the dashboard
